post_text: Good afternoon CMS and CHS families! We are excited to announce that our library is now open on Tuesdays and Thursdays to our students in 5th through 12th grade. We would love to have you come visit and select a new favorite book to read while we are still apart. To limit the number of people in the library at once, appointments are required. Please go to the school’s website and click on the link, library sign ups. If you are unable to access the internet, you can reach Mrs. Mattison at 804-491-8286 to schedule an appointment. When arriving, please enter our building through the outside door closest to the library located at the front of the CMS building. Thanks and have a great evening.

We would love to have you come visit and select a new favorite book to read while we are still apart. To limit the number of people in the library at once, appointments are required. Please go to the school’s website and click on the link, library sign ups. If you are unable to access the internet, you can reach Mrs. Mattison at 804-491-8286 to schedule an appointment. When arriving, please enter our building through the outside door closest to the library located at the front of the CMS building. Thanks and have a great evening.

post_text: CMS will continue with a focus on citizenship this year. Parents may sign off on hours but are not responsible for coming up with projects themselves. Please contact Ms. Ellinghausen if you have any questions.

post_text:
CuCPS honors and celebrates Juneteenth 2020, the 155th celebration and commemoration of the end of slavery in the United States, held annually across the nation on June 19.

Learn more about Juneteenth:

“Why Celebrating Juneteenth Is More Important Now than Ever,” an interview with Karlos Hill, professor of African and African-American studies at the University of Oklahoma at https://www.vox.com/identities/2018/6/19/17476482/juneteenth-holiday-emancipation-african-american-celebration-history.

Anthony Greene, College of Charleston African-American studies professor, explains the history of Juneteenth at https://today.cofc.edu/2018/06/18/african-american-studies-juneteenth/.

post_text:
CCES Gets New Floor

Cumberland Elementary School (CCES) is in the process of getting new flooring. The school, which was built in 1996, still had the original carpeting. Flooring had been on the list of capital improvements for quite a few years, but was not able to be funded until last year. Replacement of the floor began May 26, 2020, and it is estimated that the new floor will be complete by late July, prior to the opening of school for the 2020-2021 year. Installers have already finished the front hallway and quite a few classrooms.

New new floor will be tile, which was selected because it is durable, easy to maintain, and easier to disinfect—which is now a major concern with the current COVID-19 outbreak. Tile is also better for students and staff members who have allergies.

Dr. Chip Jones, Assistant Superintendent, while inspecting the progress of the installation, noted, “It might be looking dreary outside right now, but it’s bright inside!”

shared_text:
The Governor's School of Southside Virginia
June 17 at 5:05 PM ·

Parents and Students: We know you are anxious to hear how GSSV will open our 2020-2021 school year on August 10th. We are in communication with the 10 school divisions we serve as well as SVCC. At this time, we are unsure of our format, but please know that as soon as a decision has been made, we will share it with you. Much of how we will open depends on the capacity that SVCC opens and the plans of the home schools. Thank you for your patience and understanding during this unprecedented time.

Please reach out to the director if you have any questions (wesley.swain@southside.edu).

Thank you and stay safe!

DOE.VIRGINIA.GOV
VDOE :: Recover, Redesign, Restart 2020

Virginia Silveira Gills shared a link to the group: Cumberland County Elementary School.
June 10 at 10:23 AM ·

Good morning. We are sure you have many questions regarding the opening of school. Know that we are busy preparing for 2020-2021. While we have been working on a Return to School (R2S) plan for over a month, we now have new parameters to guide this work. When you have time to browse, you may find this information helpful. Once we have a finalized plan for Cumberland Elementary School, we will share it.In the next few weeks, there will be at least one survey shared. Your feedback it critical to our work. We will share the survey in many forms in an effort to have as much participation as possible. Thank you for your help, support, love, thoughts and prayers as we work together to design a safe Return to School Plan.

We cannot wait to be back together as One School, One Team, One Family.

Public Notice: Cumberland School Board Vacancy

The Cumberland County School Board is currently accepting letters of interest and résumés for the position of interim School Board member. Anyone interested in the position must be a qualified voter who resides in Voting District 4. All letters and résumés should be faxed to Dr. Elizabeth Jamerson at 804-492-9869 or mailed to the following address:

Cumberland County Public Schools

P. O. Box 170

Cumberland, VA 23040

All letters and résumés should be received by June 23, 2020.

A public hearing on the selection of a candidate will be held on July 2, 2020, at 7:00 P.M., during the virtual Zoom meeting. Names of candidates applying for the position will be posted on the school webpage and in the School Board Office prior to the meeting. The link for the meeting will be posted the day of the hearing. A special School Board virtual meeting will be held on July 16, 2020, at 6:30 P.M., to vote on the selection of a candidate.

"My favorite part of giving campus tours was always stopping by D-Hall. ... I would tell my tour group—before we went into the lobby—that I was taking off my name tag, and that they’d know why as soon as we walked inside. Ms. Sharon (D-Hall employee) always exclaimed, “Well, hey, Madison! How are you doing, sweetie?” I would immediately turn to my group and say, “I didn’t want to just tell you everybody here knows your name and treats you like you’re somebody. I wanted to show you." ~Madison Lewis ’19, M.E., ’20

post_text:
CHS Class of 2020:

On Tuesday June 2, CHS will have a “Diploma Drive Through“ Celebration. There will be two sessions: a morning session from 10am-12 noon and an afternoon session from 1pm -3pm.

The “Diploma Drive-Through” will have three stations:

1) A Laptop/Uniform/School book drop off station
2) A Diploma distribution station
3) A picture station

Graduates -- We ask that you arrive in your car wearing your cap and gown so that you are already dressed for the diploma and picture stations. Earned cords and stoles, previously not distributed, will be available to receive prior to the picture station.

Out of respect for social distancing protocols, please follow instructions from staff about specifically when to get in and out of cars.

We ask that graduates and parents come through the “drive through” in the same car.

We look forward to seeing our CHS Class of 2020 Graduates on Tuesday, June 2!

Cumberland High School presented the Class of 2020 Virtual Graduation on Tuesday, May 26, 2020, at 6:00 p.m.

On Tuesday, June 2, 2020, graduates will be able to individually pick up their diplomas in a drive through process and photo opportunity -- so bring your caps and gowns! More details will be forthcoming!

There is a traditional ceremony scheduled for Saturday, October 10, 2020, at 10:00 a.m.

We are providing diploma pick up next week because we felt some graduates may need their actual diploma for documentation purposes and this has been something that some parents and staff have requested.

Please continue to be patient with us as we try to meet everyone's needs.

post_text:
Thursday, May 21st, is the last day of school for the 2019-2020 school year. To celebrate the last day of school, CuCPS administration will participate in a Send off to Summer Salute by riding our school buses throughout our community. To see us ride through your part of the community, check the following link for the approximate time that we will ride by your house: https://5il.co/gb6j. Young children should be accompanied by an adult and please practice social distancing if there are multiple people at your location.

We hope to see our students' and families' smiling faces as we celebrate the last day of the 2019-2020 school year. Have a great summer!

Mrs. O's Art Studio
May 12 at 8:43 PM ·

I have always thought that hummingbirds were fascinating.

Did you know that:
Hummingbirds are the tiniest birds in the world.
A hummingbirds brain is 4% of its body weight.
Hummingbirds lay the smallest eggs of all birds.

If you are timing your studies up with Spring & Summer when hummingbirds are likely out and about this would be a fantastic project for you. Join me tomorrow Mrs. O's Art Studio to create your own!

post_text:
Congratulations to the CHS Class of 2020 Valedictorian Graceyn Cubbage and Salutatorian Jordan Smith!

The 2020 Valedictorian and Salutatorian of Cumberland High School are two highly motivated students that shine both in and out of the classroom. They have also been accepted to two of Virginia's most acclaimed universities. CHS valedictorian, Graceyn Cubbage, is the daughter of Kenny and Karen Cubbage of Farmville, Virginia. Graceyn will be attending the University of Virginia in order to major in Global Studies. Graceyn is a member of the CHS Color Guard and the National Honor Society.

Jordan Smith is the CHS salutatorian. Jordan,the son of Mr. Todd Smith and Mrs. Lacie Womack, is also a resident of Farmville, Virginia. Jordan will be attending Virginia Tech to pursue a major in Environmental Studies. Jordan is a member of the CHS varsity baseball team.

Take whatever you want and pass them on to someone else when you're finished with them. Hope you find something you like!

post_text: Because of the COVID-19 crisis, additional benefits have been identified for some of our CuCPS families. Under the Families First Coronavirus Response Act of 2020 (FFCRA), designated families will soon receive food funds through Pandemic Electronic Benefits Transfers (EBT). All elementary and middle school students will be eligible to receive funds because CuCPS participates in the Community Eligibility Provision (CEP) meal service program. Further, all high school students that are on a free or reduced meal plan also will be eligible to receive funds. This is a one-time supplemental program and funding will not be ongoing. Families will receive, via the US Postal Service, EBT debit cards along with a FAQ sheet regarding the program beginning mid-May. The Department of Social Services will be handling all funds, cards and undeliverable cards.

The Department of Social Services will be handling all funds, cards and undeliverable cards.

shared_text:
U.S. Senator Tim Kaine
April 22 at 6:38 PM ·

I’ve been thinking a lot about how many students in the Class of 2020 likely won’t be able to have their expected graduations, a time so many families looked forward to. So I wanted to give all of Virginia’s high school seniors the chance to be graduation speakers! Here’s what you can do: record a short video of a speech you’d like to share with your fellow graduating seniors and send it to gradspeech@kaine.senate.gov by May 15th. My team and I will pick the best of the best to showcase here on Facebook and show the world what Virginia’s Class of 2020 is all about. I look forward to hearing the wisdom and inspiration from Virginia’s future leaders!

CHS SENIORS: On Saturday, April 25, from 10 AM to 1 PM, CHS administration will be hosting a DRIVE-THRU SENIOR YARD SIGN HANDOUT in front of the CHS/CMS complex middle school entrance! For social distancing purposes, you and/or your parents will drive up to the middle school entrance, receive your sign through the car window, and go straight home so you can put up your sign!

The signs are beautiful and were created as a result of fundraising efforts from the Cumberland community. Starting this weekend, when people drive past your house, they will know that it is the home of a Cumberland Duke from the class of 2020! Come by on Saturday and pick up a sign! We love you and there’s absolutely nothing you can do about it! - Mr. Williams and Mrs. Long

CHS SENIORS: On Saturday, April 25, from 10 AM to 1 PM, CHS administration will be hosting a DRIVE-THRU SENIOR YARD SIGN HANDOUT in front of the CHS/CMS complex middle school entrance! For social distancing purposes, you and/or your parents will drive up to the middle school entrance, receive your sign through the car window, and go straight home so you can put up your sign!

The signs are beautiful and were created as a result of fundraising efforts from the Cumberland community. Starting this weekend, when people drive past your house, they will know that it is the home of a Cumberland Duke from the class of 2020! Come by on Saturday and pick up a sign! We love you and there’s absolutely nothing you can do about it! - Mr. Williams and Mrs. Long

CHS Yearbook
April 20 at 8:22 PM ·

Good Afternoon,

The yearbook online order site has closed, and we are no longer be able to accept online orders for the 2020 Duke. The website is designed to switch over to in-person sales at the school once the book is sent for publication. The current situation with Covid-19 will only allow us to accept mail in orders at this moment.

The website closure coincides with the final change in the yearbook price to $50 per copy. Please send orders to the address listed below. Be sure to include a short message as to how many copies you are ordering and how much you are including as payment. For example: 1 Yearbook @ $50.

As soon as we receive a publication date, it will be posted here and the school will determine the best way to make sure those who purchased books receive them.

Thank you all for your patience, and we hope that everyone remains safe and healthy.

Sincerely,
The Yearbook Staff

Send orders to:
Cumberland High School
Attention Yearbook
PO Box 140
Cumberland, VA 23040

post_text: The Cumberland County School Board will hold a meeting on April 20, 2020, with the closed session starting at 6:30 p.m., followed by the open session at 7:00 p.m. The meeting will be held electronically via Zoom, pursuant to the Emergency Ordinance adopted by the Cumberland Board of Supervisors on April 8, 2020. The agenda will be made available on the school website at https://go.boarddocs.com/vsba/ccpsva/Board.nsf/Public. A link will be posted on the website at http://www.cucps.k12.va.us on the day of the meeting for community members who wish to view the meeting. Anyone who wishes to send comments for Board members should send them to Elizabeth Jamerson, Clerk of the School Board, at ejamerson@cucps.k12.va.us by 12:00 p.m. on Monday, April 20, 2020, or should call the Central Office at 804-492-4212 between the hours of 10:00 a.m. and 12:00 noon on April 20, 2020. Community members will also have the opportunity to speak during the public comments portion of the meeting by joining the Zoom meeting and pressing the “raise your hand” button.

post_text:
Due to the Coronavirus pandemic, CuCPS school buildings and offices are closed.

Luckily, student breakfast and lunch distribution/delivery and learning continue.

If you need to contact administration, teachers, or a staff member, the best way is through email. Email addresses can be found on our CuCPS webpage. If this is not possible, you can call 804-492-4212 between the hours of 10:00 a.m. - 2:00 p.m. on weekdays. This number will be answered by Mrs. Sandra Raymond remotely. She will get your messages to the correct people.

You can also contact the following CuCPS staff members through Google Voice:

Ginny Gills, CCES Principal, 804-491-6007
Pamela Stepko, CCES Assistant Principal, 434-352-1435

Ashley Long, CHS Assistant Principal, 804-491-6607
Ashley Lawson, CHS School Counselor, 804-491-6183

Thank you for being patient, flexible, and understanding with us.

post_text:
This alert will go out later this morning.

Good Morning, CuCPS Family. There are a lot of unknowns regarding how CuCPS will proceed for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. Although our school buildings are closed, student learning is to continue. We will learn more from the Virginia Department of Education today on the expectations on how to proceed. Please be patient as we learn the expectations and then plan and prepare for remote learning.

We hope to have answers for you by Friday and develop a Frequently Asked Questions document for our staff, families, and the community as a reference. However, I can tell you now that we are committed to providing breakfast and lunch meals to our students for the remainder of the school year and will still hold prom and graduation ceremony for the Class of 2020 when it is safe to do so.

My thoughts and prayers go out to each student, family, and staff member as we navigate through this time. We are here for you. If you need something, please reach out to me at 492-4212 or through email at agriffin@cucps.k12.va.us.

Cumberland County Public Schools, VA
March 18 at 5:49 PM ·

We are establishing a food delivery process for families that cannot get to one of the three distribution sites. We prefer participation in the drive-thru process at one of the distribution sites (Randolph Fire Department, front of CMS, and Cartersville Rescue Squad building) from 10:00 a.m. - 12:00 noon; however, we do understand that some families or childcare providers are unable to get to the sites. If you are unable to get to a distribution site, please call your child’s school at 492-4212 between the hours of 2:00-3:00 p.m. and request a delivery for the next day. We will arrange meal delivery.

Again, we prefer distribution through the drive-thru process; however, we do understand that this is not possible for all families. It is our hope to provide meals for every student at Cumberland County Public Schools and we encourage each family to participate.

Beginning tomorrow, Tuesday, March 17, 2020, breakfast and lunch bags for CuCPS students will be available each weekday from 10:00 a.m. to 12:00 noon at three locations: the Randolph Fire Department, in front of CMS, and at the Cartersville Rescue Squad building.

Distribution will be done in a drive-thru manner. You will not need to get out of your car. We will bring the bagged meals to you. We ask that you keep the drive-thru lines moving.

Learning packets will be mailed home on Wednesday. Please be on the lookout for your child’s packet. Your child’s Report Card will be included in the packet.

As information evolves, plans may change. Thank you for being understanding, patient, and flexible. Stay safe and healthy. Thank you.

Governor Northam has just ordered all schools to be closed for a minimum of two weeks. CuCPS will be closed from March 16, 2020, to March 27, 2020.

We will keep in touch with families through our alert system, webpage, and social media throughout this time period in regards to instructional and food services for our students.

I encourage everyone to stay home and practice germ prevention. You can find resources from the CDC on our website. Everyone be safe and we will miss you.

shared_text:
The Governor's School of Southside Virginia
March 5 at 5:51 PM ·

Mrs. Hamilton’s and Mrs. Poling’s Humanities chemistry students were tasked with creating hand-made hot air balloons out of tissue paper as part of their study on gas laws. Calculations had to be made to determine the lift capacity of the balloon and to predict whether or not it would fly. Three balloons can be seen in the picture caught by the trees; others that took flight landed on the roof of the building. It was a very windy day compared to when STEM flew their balloons last semester but still very successful.

shared_text:
The Governor's School of Southside Virginia is with Jennifer Giordano Kinne.
February 12 at 7:49 PM ·

Keysville STEM chemistry juniors got a low tech introduction to chemical equilibrium today. Chemical equilibrium is when the forward and reverse reaction rates are equal. On a macroscopic level the reaction appears to have stopped. In the water model, the depth of water in a bin would remain the same while the water transfers were occurring. Using quantities of water to represent concentration and different sized cups to represent reaction rates, the students modeled different scenarios to observe various equilibrium positions.
text:
The Governor's School of Southside Virginia is with Jennifer Giordano Kinne.
February 12 at 7:49 PM ·

Keysville STEM chemistry juniors got a low tech introduction to chemical equilibrium today. Chemical equilibrium is when the forward and reverse reaction rates are equal. On a macroscopic level the reaction appears to have stopped. In the water model, the depth of water in a bin would remain the same while the water transfers were occurring. Using quantities of water to represent concentration and different sized cups to represent reaction rates, the students modeled different scenarios to observe various equilibrium positions.

shared_text:
The Governor's School of Southside Virginia
January 16 at 6:42 PM ·

The Governor's School of Southside Virginia is pleased to announce Wesley Swain as the new Director. Mrs. Swain took the helm of GSSV in January and is excited to begin her journey with the program. She has spent the last 16 years of her professional career in Mecklenburg County Public Schools first as an English teacher (8th and 10th grades), then as an Assistant Principal, and most recently as a Principal. She brings with her a wide range of experience and is looking to continually grow GSSV and showcase all that the program has to offer to its students and the communities.

January 16 at 6:42 PM ·

She brings with her a wide range of experience and is looking to continually grow GSSV and showcase all that the program has to offer to its students and the communities.

post_text:
The Cumberland Model UN team enjoyed a successful South Central Virginia Model United Nations Conference at Hampden-Sydney College. The students collaborated with delegates from Nottoway, Fuqua, Prince Edward, Appomattox, and Prince Edward High Schools to tackle issues such as climate change and its impact on coral reef systems, gender based violence and the refugee crisis, and the opioid crisis.

Several of Cumberland's students were recognized for their efforts during the Conference with the following awards:

Verbal Commendation (Most Improved) - Linden Czeizinger and Justin Parran (representing China)

Honorable Mention Commendation (3rd Most Outstanding Delegation) - Samantha Tillett and Ebony Arauz (representing the Russian Federation)

Best Delegation Commendation - Ramir Parker and Amir McClinton (representing Indonesia)

shared_text:
Idaho State Department of Education
November 20, 2019 at 10:55 PM ·

As part of this week's American Youth Policy Forum study tour, Idaho's delegation, made up of SDE staff and ID Senator Dave Lent, visited Cumberland County Public Schools, VA to see their student-centered deeper learning model! It was so inspiring (and fun!) to witness their hands-on robotics & programming discovery lab, passion project presentations, and student led panels on senior project development in action!
text:
Thanks for visiting and spending the day with us!

Idaho State Department of Education
November 20, 2019 at 10:55 PM ·

As part of this week's American Youth Policy Forum study tour, Idaho's delegation, made up of SDE staff and ID Senator Dave Lent, visited Cumberland County Public Schools, VA to see their student-centered deeper learning model! It was so inspiring (and fun!) to witness their hands-on robotics & programming discovery lab, passion project presentations, and student led panels on senior project development in action!

post_text:
What do state leaders and policy makers from North Dakota, Idaho, Colorado, Utah, Arkansas, and Virginia come to see at CuCPS?

They saw examples of deeper learning in the Career Connections Lab, US/VA History, DE Biology, and Earth Science. They also had discussions with teachers and students; were entertained by our Brass Quintet; and were fed delicious food by our food service department and culinary arts students.

shared_text:
Virginia Silveira Gills‎Cumberland County Elementary School
October 11, 2019 at 9:43 AM ·

Mark your calendars: Thursday, October 24, 2019, CCES will host parent conference night with a twist! Not only will you have an opportunity to meet your child’s teacher to discuss progress and learning targets, but you will also have an opportunity to learn about many after-school, weekend, summer opportunities for CCES children. Did you know the YMCA is coming to CCES? Are you ready for the next round of recreation ball? Do you know all the events that take place at our public library? Have you ever checked out all that the 4H, Bear Creek, the Scouts have to offer? What is Girls Who Code?
You won’t want to miss this day. But that’s not all.... participate in a stem activity with your child. That’s right-Parent Conference Night is sure to please all when combined with Innovation Night AND our Community Partners. Join us from 4:00-7:00. Contact your child’s teacher for a specific conference time but everything else is Open House Style. Hope you can make it!

Mark your calendars: Thursday, October 24, 2019, CCES will host parent conference night with a twist! Not only will you have an opportunity to meet your child’s teacher to discuss progress and learning targets, but you will also have an opportunity to learn about many after-school, weekend, summer opportunities for CCES children. Did you know the YMCA is coming to CCES? Are you ready for the next round of recreation ball? Do you know all the events that take place at our public library? Have you ever checked out all that the 4H, Bear Creek, the Scouts have to offer? What is Girls Who Code?
You won’t want to miss this day. But that’s not all.... participate in a stem activity with your child. That’s right-Parent Conference Night is sure to please all when combined with Innovation Night AND our Community Partners. Join us from 4:00-7:00. Contact your child’s teacher for a specific conference time but everything else is Open House Style. Hope you can make it!

Senior Tanner Cochran finished 18th in small schools Patriot division 5k out of 273 runners. Sophomore Tyler Smith ran to a 11th finish in the 2 mile Sabre division.
